# Unity DI Composition And Scopes

- Start DI from a single composition root; do not build containers outside `Bootstrap`.
- Application-level bootstrap, composition, and service initialization should stay in plain C# services; use `MonoBehaviour` only when a scene boundary is required.
- Register `App` scope services in the boot scope, and scene-bound services in the relevant scene `LifetimeScope`.
- Plain C# services, use cases, presenters, and controllers should receive dependencies through constructor injection.
- Use `RegisterComponent` or `RegisterComponentInHierarchy` for `MonoBehaviour` references; do not collect scene dependencies through `new`, `Find*`, singleton, or service locator fallback.
- Use `RegisterInstance` only for intentional singletons/config; do not lock transient use cases or services as instances.
- If initialization orchestration and scene behavior land in the same class, move init logic into a plain C# service and keep scene behavior in an adapter `MonoBehaviour`.

## Example

```csharp
// BAD: Init orchestration lives in MonoBehaviour and scene lookup
private void Awake()
{
    var saveService = FindAnyObjectByType<SaveService>();
    new AppBootstrapService(_config, saveService).Initialize();
}

// GOOD: Scope registrations expose dependencies explicitly
builder.Register<AppBootstrapService>(Lifetime.Singleton);
builder.Register<ISaveService, SaveService>(Lifetime.Singleton);
builder.RegisterComponentInHierarchy<MyHudView>();
```
